# Review: fetch-yield per-query-crash fix (I-deepfix-001 #1369)

## What happened (the bug being fixed)
A live paid run (box 1) crashed rc=1 with:
`FetchStarvationError: fetch yield 0.095 < floor 0.30 (success=6 timeout=57)` at
`live_retriever.py:_fetch_yield_gate`. Traceback: fs_researcher fans out ~50 queries
(`_ex.map(_one, _rest)`), each `_one` -> per_query_retrieve -> run_live_retrieval ->
`_fetch_yield_gate(...)` at the PER-QUERY seam. ONE throttled/niche query (6 usable of
~63 attempts under 429 pressure) raised FetchStarvationError, which propagated through
the ThreadPoolExecutor and killed the ENTIRE run — even though the AGGREGATE corpus was
healthy (731 fetched / 127 failed = 0.85 yield). The gate meant to PREVENT a starved
corpus instead CRASHED a healthy run.

## The fix (2 hunks, faithfulness-neutral)
1. `live_retriever.py` ~6317: the PER-QUERY `_fetch_yield_gate(...)` call is now wrapped
   in try/except FetchStarvationError -> DISCLOSE-ONLY (log warning + append to `notes`),
   NOT re-raised. The gate function itself is UNCHANGED (still computes rate, still emits
   the [activation] marker on pass/HALT/skip). A single query no longer kills the run.
2. `run_honest_sweep_r3.py` ~11588 (post-fetch, pre-selection seam, runs in BOTH fresh
   and resume): NEW aggregate `fetch_yield_aggregate_gate` — computes yield from the FULL
   merged `retrieval.candidates_fetched / candidates_total`; if total>=min_attempts AND
   rate<floor -> raise FetchStarvationError (the authoritative "never bank a starved
   corpus" halt, the 53/990 disaster class). Emits [activation] marker on HALT and pass.
   Env kill-switch PG_FETCH_YIELD_AGGREGATE_GATE=1 default-ON. Missing counts (total<=0)
   -> rate 1.0 -> pass (no false halt on lean resume reconstructs).

## Offline proof (already run, all pass)
- both files py_compile clean; exactly 1 call site of _fetch_yield_gate (now wrapped).
- `_fetch_yield_gate(6,57,0)` still RAISES (gate logic unchanged).
- healthy aggregate 731/858=0.852 -> pass; below-min-attempts 1/41 -> skip; disaster
  53/990=0.054 -> aggregate HALT=True.

## Review focus (verify, don't discover)
- Does the per-query catch correctly stop the crash WITHOUT swallowing a genuinely starved
  AGGREGATE (answer: aggregate gate is the authoritative halt)?
- Is `notes` in scope at the catch site? (yes — appended at ~6290 subwall path).
- Is `retrieval` in scope + are the attr names correct (candidates_fetched /
  candidates_failed_fetch / candidates_total — confirmed used identically at ~15746)?
- Any double-halt / resume false-halt risk? (resume with total<=0 -> pass by design).
- Faithfulness: does this touch strict_verify / NLI / 4-role / span-grounding? (must be NO).

